{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 19:01:32.537162", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — mini Internet (RIP + WireGuard overlay)\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- The underlay IP connectivity and RIP routing are healthy: internal hosts and servers reach each other with low latency and no packet loss.\\n- Two key anomalies contradict the intended design:\\n  1. The WireGuard VPN overlay appears inactive: the wg interfaces on host_1 and vpn_server_1 are up but carry zero packets (no tunnel traffic / no handshake).\\n  2. The external server LAN (20.0.0.0/24) is being advertised and routed across the RIP underlay, so web servers intended to be reachable only via the VPN are reachable directly from internal hosts.\\n- Localization: the problem components are the WireGuard endpoints (host_1 and vpn_server_1) and the external_router_1 (advertising the server LAN into RIP). The routing /advertisement is the mechanism enabling direct access; the VPN endpoints are the ones not forming the encrypted overlay.\\n\\nDetailed findings and evidence\\n\\n1) Underlay reachability and routing (overall health)\\n- Bulk reachability tests show essentially 0% packet loss between hosts and servers; RTTs are low and stable across the fabric (examples from get_reachability output).\\n- Individual ping from host_1 to web_server_1_1 and web_server_1_2 succeeded with small RTTs:\\n  - host_1 → web_server_1_1 (20.0.0.3): 4/4, avg RTT ~2.25 ms\\n  - host_1 → web_server_1_2 (20.0.0.4): 4/4, avg RTT ~2.45 ms\\n- FRR routing tables on routers are populated by RIP and show full propagation of both internal 10.0.X.0/24 LANs and the external 20.0.X.0/24 LANs (examples below).\\n\\n2) WireGuard VPN overlay appears inactive\\n- host_1 network config (get_host_net_config for host_1):\\n  - wg0: inet 172.16.1.11/24, state UP\\n  - wg0 packet counters: RX 0 bytes, TX 0 bytes\\n  - default route remains via 10.0.0.1 (eth0); route to 172.16.1.0/24 exists via wg0\\n- vpn_server_1 network config (get_host_net_config for vpn_server_1):\\n  - wg0: inet 172.16.1.1/24, state UP\\n  - wg0 packet counters: RX 0 bytes, TX 0 bytes\\n- Despite wg interfaces being present/up, both ends show zero packets exchanged; there is no evidence of an active WireGuard handshake or forwarded traffic across the overlay.\\n- host_1 can reach vpn_server_1 at its 20.0.0.2 address (ICMP to eth0) — the endpoint is reachable via the underlay, but WireGuard itself is not exchanging data.\\n\\n3) Server LANs are being advertised into RIP (enables direct access)\\n- external_router_1 FRR config includes:\\n  - router rip\\n    - network 192.168.0.0/16\\n    - network 20.0.0.0/24\\n- external_router_1 is therefore advertising the 20.0.0.0/24 server network into RIP. Routing tables (gateway_router and other routers) show 20.0.0.0/24 and other 20.0.X.0/24 networks learned via RIP (R entries).\\n- Example from gateway_router route output: R>* 20.0.0.0/24 [120/2] via 192.168.0.60, eth2\\n- Because the 20.0.0.0/24 prefix is present in the underlay routing fabric, internal hosts reach 20.0.0.X addresses directly over the underlay — demonstrated by the successful pings from host_1 to web_server_1_1/1_2.\\n\\n4) Security / policy mismatch (intent vs observed)\\n- Intended design per description: web_server_1_1 and web_server_1_2 should be accessible only via the VPN overlay (WireGuard).\\n- Observed state: those web servers are reachable directly using the underlay IP addresses (20.0.0.X) without any WireGuard tunnel traffic. That indicates a policy enforcement gap: the underlay routing advertises the server LAN and there is no network-level restriction preventing direct access.\\n\\nAdditional observations / minor findings\\n- gateway_router running config contains an odd line \"network None\" in its RIP stanza — likely a configuration artifact. Despite that, gateway_router has appropriate RIP-learned routes in its routing table.\\n- vpn_server_1 eth0 shows a small rx-drop count (RX dropped 1) in ifconfig output; not necessarily material, but noted.\\n- All FRR routers are redistributing static and advertising many 192.168.0.x /31 infra links and LAN prefixes — RIP propagation appears consistent and converged (routes have similar ages).\\n\\nLocalization (faulty / implicated devices)\\n- WireGuard endpoints:\\n  - host_1 (client): wg0 present but 0 packets — indicates client-side WireGuard not negotiating / not sending/receiving tunneling traffic.\\n  - vpn_server_1 (server): wg0 present but 0 packets — indicates server-side WireGuard not negotiating / not receiving handshake.\\n  These two endpoints are where the VPN overlay is failing to form.\\n- external_router_1:\\n  - Configured to include 20.0.0.0/24 in RIP and therefore is responsible for advertising the server LAN into the underlay. This action is the proximate cause that allows direct reachability to the web servers without the VPN overlay.\\n\\nProbable root causes (inferred)\\n- WireGuard tunnel down / misconfigured:\\n  - Either WireGuard peer configuration (keys, allowed IPs, endpoint, port) is mismatched on one or both ends, or the WireGuard service/daemon is not performing the handshake. Evidence: wg interfaces exist and are UP but show zero packet counters on both ends.\\n  - Underlay connectivity between host_1 and vpn_server_1 exists (ICMP to 20.0.0.2 works), so UDP/endpoint reachability is not the primary blocker — the failure is specific to WireGuard handshake/peer config or service-level operation.\\n- Routing and policy misconfiguration:\\n  - external_router_1 advertises the server LAN into RIP (intent mismatch). Because 20.0.0.0/24 is globally routable across the RIP mesh, the servers are reachable directly from internal subnets without the VPN. This is a configuration/policy error relative to the design goal (VPN-only access).\\n\\nSummary (concise)\\n- Network fabric (underlay, RIP) is healthy and converged.\\n- The WireGuard overlay is not functioning: wg interfaces are up but carry no traffic — host_1 and vpn_server_1 are not establishing an encrypted tunnel.\\n- The server LAN (20.0.0.0/24) is being advertised into RIP by external_router_1, enabling direct underlay access to web servers that should have been reachable only via VPN. This is a policy/routing configuration issue enabling the observed security breach.\\n- Root causes are (1) inactive/misconfigured WireGuard endpoints (host_1 and vpn_server_1) and (2) routing/policy misconfiguration on external_router_1 (advertising server LAN into the underlay).\\n\\nIf you want, I can next:\\n- Gather WireGuard-specific status (peer configs, handshake state) and/or show WireGuard service logs on host_1 and vpn_server_1 to further pinpoint why the tunnel is not negotiating; and\\n- Show iptables / firewall rules on external_router_1 and the servers to confirm whether packet filtering was intended but not applied.\\n\\n(Per your instruction I have not provided remediations — only diagnostics and localization.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='259def21-52c4-49fa-95c8-ef041ebbce0b'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
